{{Infobox football official | name = Joseph Lamptey | image = | caption | fullname = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|9|10|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Accra]], [[Ghana]] | death_date = | death_place = | otheroccupation = Senior Immigration Officer | years1 = | league1 = | role1 = | internationalyears1 = ?–2017 | confederation1 = | internationalrole1 = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]] }}
'''Joseph Lamptey''' (born on 10 September 1974 in [[Accra]]) is a former [[Ghana|Ghanaian]] [[association football]] [[referee (association football)|referee]].
Lamptey was born in [[Accra]]. He refereed at the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations]] and the [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2016 Olympics]].<ref name="BBC">{{cite news|title=World Cup qualifier between South Africa and Senegal to be replayed|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41182108|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=6 September 2017}}</ref>
[[FIFA]] banned Lamptey for life in March 2017 following allegations he manipulated the result of a match between [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] and [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] in a [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2018 FIFA World Cup]] qualifying match on 12 November 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/sep/06/south-africa-senegal-world-cup-qualifier-replayed|title=South Africa v Senegal World Cup qualifier to be replayed after referee ban|agency=Associated Press|date=2017-09-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> During the match, Lamptey wrongly awarded a penalty against Senegal's [[Kalidou Koulibaly]], leading to a complaint by the [[Senegal Football Association]]. Following the upholding of Lamptey's ban by the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]], FIFA announced the match would be replayed.<ref name="BBC" />
