{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}} {{More citations needed|date=November 2015}} {{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = SCG Stadium | former_names = Thunderdome Stadium | image = SCG Stadium 2017.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = | location = [[Pak Kret District|Bang Phut, Pak Kret]], [[Nonthaburi Province|Nonthaburi]], [[Thailand]] | coordinates = {{coord|13.917989|100.547411|format=dms|type:landmark_scale:3000}} | opened = 1998 | owner = Sports Authority of Thailand (SAT) | operator = [[Muangthong United F.C.|Muangthong United]] | surface = Grass | construction_cost = | tenants = [[Muangthong United F.C.|Muangthong United]] | seating_capacity = 15,000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mtutd.tv/team.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220083719/http://mtutd.tv/team.asp |archivedate=20 February 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> | publictransit = {{rint|bangkok|Pink}} [[Pink Line (Bangkok)|Si Rat]] ''(from 2022)'' }}
The '''Thunderdome Stadium''', currently known for sponsorship purposes as '''SCG Stadium''' is a [[List of football stadiums in Thailand|football stadium]] located in [[Muang Thong Thani]], [[Nonthaburi Province|Nonthaburi]], [[Thailand]], and is the home of [[Thai League 1]]'s side, [[Muangthong United]]. SCG Stadium was the first operate [[List of football stadiums in Thailand|football stadium]] in Thailand.
==History== [[File:ScG Stadium.jpg|200px|thumb|left|inside the stadium]] SCG Stadium has been the home venue of Muangthong United since 2007. Owned by Sports Authority of Thailand, rented by Muangthong United, the stadium originally known as '''Thunderdome Sports Complex''', it opened in 1998 and had only one main stand before the [[Thai League 1]] promotion in 2009. After the promotion to the [[Thai League T1|top division]] of Muangthong United, the club started to develop the stadium, construct other temporary stands to hold the demands of the supporter. In 2010, after the club clinched its first ever [[2009 Thai Premier League|top division]], SCG stadium was developed into the 4 stands stadium with full installed seats. The capacity rose to 15,000. [[File:Thunderdome.JPG|thumb|West stand]]
==Name== The name of the ground changed twice due to sponsorship agreements, the first time it was changed from the original name, '''Thunderdome Stadium''', to '''Yamaha Stadium''' following the sponsorship in 2010. In 2012, The stadium was changed its alias to '''SCG Stadium''' following the club title sponsor of [[Siam Cement|SCG]]. However, the stadium is still referred as its official name of Thunderdome Stadium in [[Asian Football Federation|AFC]] competitions.
==Capacity== The stadium used to be able to hold as much as 20,000 spectators but the number reduce after renovation by filling in chairs to make the stadium all seated with the capacity of 15,000 people.<ref>http://www.thaiticketmajor.com/venue/details.php?vid=10156&la=en</ref> [[File:Mtutd ultra muangthong.jpg|thumb|Supporter Stand]]
==Other events== On November 25, 2012, [[K-pop]] artists under [[S.M. Entertainment]] featuring [[Kangta]], [[BoA]], [[TVXQ]], [[Super Junior]], [[Girls' Generation]], [[Shinee|SHINee]], [[f(x) (band)|f(x)]] and [[EXO (band)|EXO]], performed the world tour [[SMTown Live World Tour III|SMTown Live World Tour III in Bangkok]] in the stadium.<ref>https://processic418.wordpress.com/2012/11/04/review-scg-stadium/</ref>
The stadium hosted Korean Pop Sensation [[Psy (entertainer)|Psy]] on 28 November 2012.
[[Clash (Thai band)|Clash]] played their final concert here on April 30, 2014, followed by their disbandment.
[[Guns N' Roses]] played here on February 28, 2017 as part of their [[Not in This Lifetime... Tour]].
